Q14:
In my most recent photo book creation experience, I wished there was a way more easily adapt the “auto fill template” option after the auto fill. I want to be able to customize for a striking appearance but not have to keep checking how many other places the auto fill placed the same photo. Some way to determine how many times a photo is used, and a warning if it’s a duplicate from another part of the book... that’s honestly the most time consuming. 

Also would LOVE the books to come more like sturdy heritage paper with blank beautiful pages here and there throughout to continue telling the story through the years, like scrapbooking in a recreated photo or jotting down a memory associated with photos on nearby pages. I prefer to add captions by hand as I savor the created book. If it comes to me completed, I will leave it on a shelf somewhere because the creativity is complete.

Q14: I am a photographer, professional photo organizer, and also design custom photo books, in addition to my personal books. My most recent mpix order was the same book design, ordered as both economy and premium books for comparison. It was very frustrating to not be able to easily design/edit the spine. The premium book had the cover photo bled to the center of the spine - why? This was not visible in the design process. I was also surprised that the premium lay flat book did not include end pages, which I did not realize until the books arrived. Overall, I am delighted with the color and print quality of both books! The premium book’s lay flat paper is outstanding. The economy binding is very poor and I will not order again or recommend to my clients/followers. This survey does not really address materials, which I really prioritize. I strongly dislike the feel of the soft touch cover that mpix offers and wish there were a better matte option. No other service can compare to the fulfillment and shipping times that mpix provides + overall quality! I do hope to see improvement in needed areas.

Q14:
Mixbook: Positives- Simple layouts that are easily customizable. Layouts are organized by the number of photos the user wants on each page. Variety of colored and patterned background to use if desired. “Stickers” which include designed typography elements and clip art (I usually only use the typography stickers). Spell check! Photos are organized by date taken. 

Negatives- No grid system option. Does not have the ability to rotate an image inside of a graphic box. Can not create photo cutouts to remove image backgrounds. Usually offered for a high price but coupons are sent regularly for 20%-40% off. I’d rather just pay a cheaper rate and not wait for a coupon to come. As a working mom I have a limited free time. When I finish a book I want to purchase it and be done. I hate waiting a month or more to get a good coupon so I can save hundreds of dollars. 

Shutterfly: I have used it but I don’t use it often be use I think it’s too scrapbook-ish. I prefer a more minimalistic style. I don’t use picture backgrounds or clip art and Shutterfly has a lot of that. 

I am going to try Blurb next because I just discovered it this year and it seems to fit my style.
